Project Proposal 

Title
Forecasting 2026 Formula 1 Team Performance Across Regulation Resets Using Recurrent Neural Networks

Research Question
Can a recurrent neural network trained on historical Formula 1 team pace data across multiple regulation resets learn performance patterns and generalize to forecast relative team pace for the 2026 season? 

Introduction
Formula 1 is the pinnacle of motorsports. 10 teams, 2 drivers per team, racing all year round for the title of champion. 
This project will analyse team pace trends and predict the average lap time delta (relative to the fast team) for the upcoming system. 
Since 2014, F1 has gone through three major technical regulation changes (2014, 2017, 2022). 
The 2026 Formula 1 season will introduce new regulations. There is now active aero in the front and rear wings. The cars are now smaller and lighter, all done to improve wheel-to-wheel racing. 
The power unit has been split 50/50, with half powered by an internal combustion engine and the other half by an electric battery, using 100% sustainable, net-zero carbon fuels. 
These regulation changes make it an interesting and challenging forecasting challenge. 
Rather than predicting exact race outcomes for teams and drivers, this project uses a recurrent neural network (RNN), specifically a gated recurrent unit (GRU), to learn team performance dynamics across past regulation resets and forecast relative team pace entering the 2026 season. 

Formula 1 has a long history of shifting team identities, but 2026 marks a big milestone. Cadillac becomes the newest team to join, expanding the grid to 11 teams. 
Thus, Cadillac will not be represented in this project. 

Analytical Plan
To simulate generalization across regulation resets:
Train on 2014-2016 → Test on 2017
Train on 2014-2021 → Test on 2022
Final model: Train on 2014-2025 → Forecast 2026
